1
00:00:06,298 --> 00:00:08,091
(WHIRRING)

2
00:00:10,636 --> 00:00:14,932
The prototype
has passed every test, sir. It's working.

3
00:00:15,599 --> 00:00:19,353
I hardly think "working" is the correct word.

4
00:00:22,940 --> 00:00:26,318
That would apply only to machines.

5
00:00:26,485 --> 00:00:30,489
I'm sorry. I should say, "It's alive.”

6
00:00:31,949 --> 00:00:35,035
-Can it hear me?
-It might still be in shock.

7
00:00:35,118 --> 00:00:38,830
Bear in mind the brain has been
welded to the exoskeleton.

8
00:00:38,956 --> 00:00:41,124
Skin of metal.

9
00:00:45,462 --> 00:00:49,383
And a body that will never age or die.

10
00:00:50,842 --> 00:00:54,221
I envy it. Do you know me?

11
00:00:55,013 --> 00:00:58,559
Answer. Do you know me?

12
00:00:59,476 --> 00:01:01,645
You are John Lumic.

13
00:01:04,106 --> 00:01:05,524
My child.

14
00:01:05,607 --> 00:01:10,737
Mark this day, Dr Kendrick. We are blessed.

15
00:01:10,821 --> 00:01:14,533
Well, it's not quite over yet, sir.
We need Geneva's approval.

16
00:01:14,616 --> 00:01:19,204
Technically, this is a new form of life,
and that contravenes the Bio-Convention.

17
00:01:19,329 --> 00:01:21,039
They'd need to ratify this.

18
00:01:21,123 --> 00:01:23,041
And they will refuse me.

19
00:01:23,166 --> 00:01:25,043
Nonetheless, we need to tell them.

20
00:01:25,127 --> 00:01:26,712
And if I don't?

21
00:01:26,795 --> 00:01:31,341
Well, I'm sorry, sir, but it's my duty.
I shall have to inform them.

22
00:01:31,425 --> 00:01:35,178
And how will you do that
from beyond the grave?

23
00:01:36,430 --> 00:01:38,515
I don't quite understand.

24
00:01:39,558 --> 00:01:40,892
Kill him.

25
00:01:50,861 --> 00:01:53,030
-Captain.
-Yes, sir?

26
00:01:53,155 --> 00:01:57,868
Inform all staff we have a new destination.

27
00:01:58,994 --> 00:02:00,704
Set sail

28
00:02:00,787 --> 00:02:02,623
for Great Britain!

29
00:02:04,249 --> 00:02:06,460
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

30
00:02:40,619 --> 00:02:43,038
DOCTOR: ...and that weird munchkin lady
with the big eyes.

31
00:02:43,121 --> 00:02:44,706
You remember the way she looked at you?

32
00:02:44,790 --> 00:02:46,500
Then she opens her mouth
and fire comes out!

33
00:02:46,583 --> 00:02:48,043
ROSE: I thought I was gonna get frazzled!

34
00:02:48,126 --> 00:02:51,421
Yeah, one minute she's standing there,
the next minute, roar!

35
00:02:52,589 --> 00:02:54,424
Where was that? What happened?

36
00:02:54,508 --> 00:02:57,469
Oh, it was on this...er, planet thing.

37
00:02:57,594 --> 00:03:00,681
Asteroid. It's a long story.
You had to be there.

38
00:03:00,764 --> 00:03:02,599
What are you doing that for?

39
00:03:02,683 --> 00:03:04,476
'Cause you told me to.

40
00:03:04,559 --> 00:03:06,103
When was that?

41
00:03:06,770 --> 00:03:08,647
About half an hour ago.

42
00:03:08,730 --> 00:03:12,109
Um... You can let go now.

43
00:03:14,778 --> 00:03:17,447
Well, how long's it been
since I could've stopped?

44
00:03:17,531 --> 00:03:21,451
Ten minutes. Twenty. Twenty nine.

45
00:03:21,910 --> 00:03:25,163
-You just forgot me!
-No, no, no, I was just...

46
00:03:25,288 --> 00:03:28,083
I was calibrating.
I know exactly what I'm doing.

47
00:03:41,430 --> 00:03:44,266
-What's happened?
-The time vortex. It's gone.

48
00:03:44,349 --> 00:03:46,852
That's impossible. It's just gone!

49
00:03:48,645 --> 00:03:51,481
Brace yourselves! We're gonna crash!

50
00:03:58,071 --> 00:04:00,240
Everyone all right? Rose? Mickey?

51
00:04:00,323 --> 00:04:02,284
I'm fine, I'm okay, sorry, yeah.

52
00:04:06,788 --> 00:04:09,166
DOCTOR: She's dead.

53
00:04:10,834 --> 00:04:12,711
The Tardis is dead.

54
00:04:13,336 --> 00:04:15,338
You can fix it.

55
00:04:15,422 --> 00:04:19,176
There's nothing to fix. She's perished.

56
00:04:22,471 --> 00:04:26,224
The last Tardis in the universe. Extinct.

57
00:04:28,018 --> 00:04:30,604
ROSE: We can get help, yeah?

58
00:04:30,687 --> 00:04:32,606
Where from?

59
00:04:32,689 --> 00:04:35,025
Well, we've landed.
We've got to be somewhere.

60
00:04:35,192 --> 00:04:38,695
We fell out of the vortex,
through the void, into nothingness.

61
00:04:40,030 --> 00:04:43,074
We're in some sort of no place.

62
00:04:43,158 --> 00:04:47,329
The Silent Realm. The Lost Dimension.

63
00:04:47,412 --> 00:04:49,873
Otherwise known as London.

64
00:04:53,585 --> 00:04:56,713
London, England, Earth! Hold on...

65
00:05:00,091 --> 00:05:04,054
It's the 1st of February. This year.
Not exactly far flung, is it?

66
00:05:04,137 --> 00:05:06,181
-So this is London?
-Yup.

67
00:05:06,264 --> 00:05:07,974
-Your city?
-That's the one.

68
00:05:08,058 --> 00:05:10,143
-Just as we left it?
-Bang on.

69
00:05:10,227 --> 00:05:12,771
And that includes the zeppelins?

70
00:05:15,524 --> 00:05:17,234
What the hell?

71
00:05:17,317 --> 00:05:19,236
That's beautiful.

72
00:05:20,362 --> 00:05:23,615
Okay, so it's London
with a big International Zeppelin Festival.

73
00:05:23,698 --> 00:05:25,700
DOCTOR: This is not your world.

74
00:05:25,784 --> 00:05:30,413
But if the date's the same...
It's parallel, right?

75
00:05:30,747 --> 00:05:33,166
Am I right? Like a parallel Earth
only they've got zeppelins?

76
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:35,627
-Am I right? I'm right, aren't I?
-Must be.

77
00:05:35,710 --> 00:05:38,922
-A parallel world where...
-Come on, you've seen it on films.

78
00:05:39,005 --> 00:05:42,676
Like an alternative to our world where
everything's the same but a little different.

79
00:05:42,759 --> 00:05:46,429
Like, I don't know, traffic lights are blue,
Tony Blair never got elected...

80
00:05:46,513 --> 00:05:48,765
And he's still alive.

81
00:05:50,684 --> 00:05:54,062
A parallel world where my dad's still alive.

82
00:05:55,355 --> 00:05:59,150
Don't look at it, Rose. Don't even
think about it. This is not your world.

83
00:05:59,276 --> 00:06:01,528
He's my dad. And...

84
00:06:02,445 --> 00:06:04,447
Trust me on this.

85
00:06:05,282 --> 00:06:08,535
Oh, that's weird. But he's real...

86
00:06:08,618 --> 00:06:11,371
-Trust me on this.
-He's a success.

87
00:06:11,454 --> 00:06:13,832
He was always planning
these daft little schemes,

88
00:06:13,957 --> 00:06:17,127
health food drinks and stuff.
Everyone said they were useless.

89
00:06:17,210 --> 00:06:18,295
But he did it.

90
00:06:18,378 --> 00:06:20,881
Rose, if you ever trusted me,
then listen to me now.

91
00:06:20,964 --> 00:06:24,134
Stop looking at him. Your father's dead.

92
00:06:24,301 --> 00:06:28,805
He died when you were six months old.
That is not your Pete. That is a Pete.

93
00:06:28,889 --> 00:06:31,224
For all we know he's got his own Jackie.
His own Rose.

94
00:06:31,308 --> 00:06:35,562
His own daughter who is someone else,
but not you. You can't see him.

95
00:06:35,645 --> 00:06:37,480
Not ever.

96
00:06:38,106 --> 00:06:42,694
Trust me on this. Trust me on this.
Trust me on this. Trust me on this.

97
00:07:11,139 --> 00:07:15,310
Hello? Sweetheart? Only me.

98
00:07:16,728 --> 00:07:19,522
Oh, the bad penny. Was this your idea?

99
00:07:19,648 --> 00:07:22,609
Don't deny it.
It's got your fingerprints all over it.

100
00:07:22,692 --> 00:07:24,110
"Trust me on this."

101
00:07:24,194 --> 00:07:26,571
Oh, I can trust you all right.
Trust you to cock it up.

102
00:07:26,655 --> 00:07:29,074
-What have I done now?
-Have a look.

103
00:07:37,916 --> 00:07:41,670
-What's wrong with that?
-40! It says 40.

104
00:07:41,753 --> 00:07:45,298
-You are 40.
-I don't want the whole world telling, do I?

105
00:07:45,382 --> 00:07:48,426
-You're having a party tonight!
-My 39th!

106
00:07:48,510 --> 00:07:52,472
My official biography says I was born
on the same day as Cuba Gooding, Jr.

107
00:07:52,597 --> 00:07:54,766
And that makes me 39,
thank you very much.

108
00:07:54,891 --> 00:07:57,894
Rose. Come here. Rose.

109
00:08:00,230 --> 00:08:03,233
These are from the girls in the office.
Happy birthday.

110
00:08:05,068 --> 00:08:08,363
I've got hand sculpted arrangements by
Veronica of Reykjavik

111
00:08:08,446 --> 00:08:11,950
and your secretary stopped off at a garage.
I don't think so.

112
00:08:12,033 --> 00:08:14,327
And if you're giving out presents,
where's my zeppelin?

113
00:08:14,411 --> 00:08:17,956
Everyone else has got one.
Rose! Come on, Rose!

114
00:08:18,748 --> 00:08:23,336
Bet you didn't even notice, did you?
Special delivery. Got sent round today.

115
00:08:23,461 --> 00:08:26,589
Birthday present from Mr Lumic,
latest model.

116
00:08:26,673 --> 00:08:30,260
Diamond studded.
Pick up signals from Venezuela.

117
00:08:30,343 --> 00:08:32,846
Why would you want to pick up signals
from Venezuela?

118
00:08:32,929 --> 00:08:38,184
Well, I don't know, but now I can find out!
For God's sake, where is she? Rose!

119
00:08:38,268 --> 00:08:41,312
She needs a good bath before tonight
or she's gonna be honking. Rose!

120
00:08:41,396 --> 00:08:43,648
Come to mummy, come on!

121
00:08:43,732 --> 00:08:45,984
There you are, my darling.

122
00:08:46,943 --> 00:08:48,611
(BEEPING)

123
00:08:48,903 --> 00:08:50,613
Mr Lumic!

124
00:08:50,697 --> 00:08:53,366
Jackie was just saying thank you.
That's very kind of you.

125
00:08:53,450 --> 00:08:57,454
Those Ear Pods are handmade.
Tell her to take care.

126
00:08:57,829 --> 00:08:59,456
Course I will. Course I will.

127
00:08:59,539 --> 00:09:02,792
I don't suppose you'll be joining us tonight,
for the party?

128
00:09:02,876 --> 00:09:04,586
We'd be very honoured.

129
00:09:04,669 --> 00:09:08,381
The world below can party.
Some of us have work to do.

130
00:09:08,465 --> 00:09:12,927
My plans have advanced, Peter.
The President has promised a decision.

131
00:09:13,011 --> 00:09:16,723
I'm flying in now.
We will be at the airstrip by 5:00.

132
00:09:16,806 --> 00:09:21,770
Right. It's just that I promised
I'd help the wife out tonight.

133
00:09:21,895 --> 00:09:25,940
If the President of Great Britain
can make this meeting, then so can you.

134
00:09:26,024 --> 00:09:27,609
He's not married to Jackie, is he?

135
00:09:27,692 --> 00:09:31,446
5:00, Mr Tyler. A famous day!

136
00:09:36,034 --> 00:09:38,787
Voice print access, John Lumic.

137
00:09:39,245 --> 00:09:42,040
Initiate Ear Pod override.

138
00:09:43,917 --> 00:09:46,503
Subject: Jacqueline Tyler.

139
00:09:50,006 --> 00:09:51,382
LUMIC: Activate.

140
00:09:52,634 --> 00:09:58,056
Download. Tyler residence.
February the 1st.

141
00:09:58,640 --> 00:10:04,562
Give me security arrangements
for tonight, passwords, encryption services.

142
00:10:14,364 --> 00:10:15,990
And restore.

143
00:10:23,206 --> 00:10:25,208
Thank you, Mrs Tyler.

144
00:10:27,001 --> 00:10:29,212
Activate picture link.

145
00:10:30,630 --> 00:10:32,173
Mr Crane.

146
00:10:32,257 --> 00:10:34,050
Mr Lumic.

147
00:10:34,134 --> 00:10:37,762
Events are moving faster
than I anticipated.

148
00:10:37,846 --> 00:10:40,223
I need extra staff.

149
00:10:40,431 --> 00:10:43,351
Very good, sir.
I shall go on a recruitment drive.

150
00:10:44,894 --> 00:10:46,396
Back her up.

151
00:10:57,115 --> 00:10:59,868
DOCTOR: I told you to keep an eye on her.
MICKEY: She's all right.

152
00:10:59,951 --> 00:11:01,828
She goes wandering off...

153
00:11:01,911 --> 00:11:04,247
A parallel world,
it's like a gingerbread house.

154
00:11:04,372 --> 00:11:06,332
All those temptations calling her.

155
00:11:06,416 --> 00:11:08,835
So it's just Rose, then?
Nothing out there to tempt me?

156
00:11:08,918 --> 00:11:10,879
Well, I don't know.
I can't worry about everything!

157
00:11:10,962 --> 00:11:13,923
If I could just get this thing to...

158
00:11:14,048 --> 00:11:15,717
-Did that help?
-Yes.

159
00:11:15,800 --> 00:11:18,136
-Did that hurt?
-Yes. Ow.

160
00:11:33,902 --> 00:11:35,945
(ZEPPELINS WHIRRING)

161
00:11:49,417 --> 00:11:51,294
(BEEPING)

162
00:11:57,175 --> 00:11:59,302
...and it's good news for Great Britain

163
00:11:59,385 --> 00:12:01,846
as John Lumic returns
to the country of his birth.

164
00:12:01,930 --> 00:12:04,641
Mr Lumic, the inventor of
High Content metal,

165
00:12:04,724 --> 00:12:07,310
has denied allegations of ill health.

166
00:12:07,393 --> 00:12:12,440
We're all flesh and blood,
but the brain is what makes us human.

167
00:12:13,107 --> 00:12:16,402
And my mind is more creative than ever.

168
00:12:16,486 --> 00:12:19,322
With shares in Cybus Industries
doubling in price,

169
00:12:19,405 --> 00:12:23,743
Mr Lumic has pledged more support
for the homeless in New South America.

170
00:12:23,826 --> 00:12:25,203
In other news.

171
00:12:25,286 --> 00:12:29,290
The Torchwood Institute has published
a study claiming that...

172
00:12:30,124 --> 00:12:32,543
We're not meant to be here.

173
00:12:33,002 --> 00:12:36,923
The Tardis draws its power from
the universe but it's the wrong universe.

174
00:12:37,006 --> 00:12:39,550
It's like diesel in a petrol engine.

175
00:12:40,551 --> 00:12:43,096
But I've seen it in comics,
people go hopping

176
00:12:43,179 --> 00:12:46,057
from one alternative world to another.
It's easy!

177
00:12:46,182 --> 00:12:48,101
Not in the real world.

178
00:12:49,269 --> 00:12:50,812
Used to be easy.

179
00:12:50,895 --> 00:12:52,730
When the Time Lords
kept their eye on everything,

180
00:12:52,855 --> 00:12:55,817
you could pop between realities,
home in time for tea.

181
00:12:56,526 --> 00:12:59,362
Then they died and took it all with them.

182
00:13:00,655 --> 00:13:03,866
The walls of reality closed.
The worlds were sealed.

183
00:13:04,534 --> 00:13:07,245
Everything became that bit less kind.

184
00:13:07,787 --> 00:13:11,874
-Then how did we get here?
-I don't know. Accident.

185
00:13:13,459 --> 00:13:16,296
Should've been impossible,
now we're trapped.

186
00:13:19,924 --> 00:13:21,217
What's that?

187
00:13:22,260 --> 00:13:23,344
What?

188
00:13:23,428 --> 00:13:25,888
That there. Is that a reflection?

189
00:13:29,225 --> 00:13:33,896
It's a light! Is it? Is that a light?
I think that's a light.

190
00:13:33,980 --> 00:13:38,568
That's all we need. We've got power!
Mickey, we've got power!

191
00:13:46,826 --> 00:13:51,205
Gentlemen, gentlemen!
I beg your attention!

192
00:13:51,289 --> 00:13:54,625
Christmas has come early
so come and get it!

193
00:13:55,877 --> 00:13:58,546
Oh, smell that, comrades!

194
00:13:58,629 --> 00:14:01,466
Burgers and chips! Sausage and beans!

195
00:14:01,549 --> 00:14:06,012
Pork, chicken and hot sweet tea.
All for free!

196
00:14:06,095 --> 00:14:08,389
-Don't go!
-But there's food.

197
00:14:08,473 --> 00:14:10,433
All you can eat, free of charge!

198
00:14:10,516 --> 00:14:14,312
Don't just stand there.
Fill your faces with pasties...

199
00:14:14,395 --> 00:14:15,521
They're lying.

200
00:14:15,605 --> 00:14:18,608
It's easy for you to say.
When did you last starve?

201
00:14:18,733 --> 00:14:21,444
All those people
disappearing off the streets.

202
00:14:21,527 --> 00:14:25,615
It's been going on for months. It's them.

203
00:14:25,740 --> 00:14:28,868
-They're taking you away.
-What for?

204
00:14:28,993 --> 00:14:30,661
Experiments.

205
00:14:32,830 --> 00:14:34,540
I'm so hungry.

206
00:14:35,291 --> 00:14:37,293
So come and get it while it's hot!

207
00:14:37,418 --> 00:14:41,547
That's it, kind sir,
get in there and fill your face!

208
00:14:41,631 --> 00:14:44,342
Feast yourself, brother, feast yourself.

209
00:14:44,425 --> 00:14:45,718
(SCREAMING)

210
00:14:45,802 --> 00:14:48,096
-What are you doing!
-Take them away.

211
00:14:48,179 --> 00:14:50,223
No! No! Help!

212
00:14:52,975 --> 00:14:54,811
DOCTOR: It's alive!

213
00:14:55,686 --> 00:14:57,188
-What is it?
-Nothing.

214
00:14:57,313 --> 00:15:00,274
It's tiny. It's one of those
insignificant little power cells

215
00:15:00,358 --> 00:15:03,111
that no one ever bothers about
and it's clinging on to life!

216
00:15:03,236 --> 00:15:05,905
It's got one little ounce of reality,
tucked away inside.

217
00:15:05,988 --> 00:15:07,573
Enough to get us home?

218
00:15:07,657 --> 00:15:09,158
Not yet.

219
00:15:10,159 --> 00:15:12,328
I need to charge it up.

220
00:15:13,329 --> 00:15:15,415
We could go outside
and lash it up to the national grid.

221
00:15:15,498 --> 00:15:18,251
Wrong sort of energy.
It's got to come from our universe.

222
00:15:18,334 --> 00:15:19,961
But we don't have anything.

223
00:15:20,044 --> 00:15:21,504
There's me.

224
00:15:29,887 --> 00:15:34,308
I just gave away 10 years of my life.
Worth every second.

225
00:15:45,236 --> 00:15:46,904
It's going out. Is that okay?

226
00:15:47,029 --> 00:15:50,533
It's on a recharging cycle.
It'll loop round, power back up

227
00:15:50,658 --> 00:15:54,370
and be ready to take us home in 24 hours.

228
00:15:55,288 --> 00:15:57,457
So that gives us 24 hours
on a parallel world?

229
00:15:57,540 --> 00:15:58,791
Shore leave.

230
00:15:58,875 --> 00:16:02,753
So long as we keep our heads down,
easy, no problem. Let's go and tell her.

231
00:16:03,379 --> 00:16:07,383
There you are!
It's all right, no applause, I fixed it.

232
00:16:08,050 --> 00:16:11,053
24 hours
and then we're flying back to reality.

233
00:16:13,681 --> 00:16:15,057
What is it?

234
00:16:16,267 --> 00:16:21,439
My phone connected. There's this
Cybus network. It finds your phone.

235
00:16:23,983 --> 00:16:26,194
It gave me internet access.

236
00:16:26,319 --> 00:16:29,614
Rose, whatever it says,
this is the wrong world.

237
00:16:30,698 --> 00:16:33,659
-I don't exist.
-What do you mean?

238
00:16:33,743 --> 00:16:36,454
There's no Rose Tyler. I was never born.

239
00:16:36,579 --> 00:16:38,873
There's Pete, my dad, and Jackie.

240
00:16:38,956 --> 00:16:42,084
He still married Mum
but they never had kids.

241
00:16:42,210 --> 00:16:43,628
Give me that phone.

242
00:16:44,587 --> 00:16:50,092
They're rich. They've got a house
and cars and everything they want.

243
00:16:52,512 --> 00:16:54,472
But they haven't got me.

244
00:17:00,603 --> 00:17:02,688
-I've got to see them.
-You can't.

245
00:17:02,772 --> 00:17:05,024
-I just want to see them.
-I can't let you.

246
00:17:05,107 --> 00:17:08,444
-You just said 24 hours.
-You can't become their daughter.

247
00:17:08,528 --> 00:17:10,571
That's not the way it works.
Mickey, tell her.

248
00:17:10,655 --> 00:17:12,198
24 hours, yeah?

249
00:17:12,281 --> 00:17:14,659
-Where are you going?
-Well, I can do what I want.

250
00:17:14,784 --> 00:17:16,369
I've got the address and everything.

251
00:17:16,452 --> 00:17:18,746
Stay where you are! Both of you!
Rose, come back!

252
00:17:18,829 --> 00:17:21,958
-Mickey, come back here! Right now!
-I just want to see them.

253
00:17:22,083 --> 00:17:24,752
-Yeah, I've got things to see and all.
-Like what?

254
00:17:24,835 --> 00:17:27,880
You don't know anything
about me, do you? It's always about Rose.

255
00:17:27,964 --> 00:17:30,049
I'm just a spare part.

256
00:17:30,132 --> 00:17:32,385
I'm sorry, I've got to go.

257
00:17:34,470 --> 00:17:37,223
Go on, then. There's no choice, is there?

258
00:17:37,306 --> 00:17:41,310
You can only chase after one of us
and it's never gonna be me, is it?

259
00:17:44,146 --> 00:17:46,440
Back here. 24 hours.

260
00:17:47,316 --> 00:17:50,444
Yeah. If I haven't found something better.

261
00:18:12,466 --> 00:18:15,636
Mr Tyler, what's the matter
couldn't wait until tonight?

262
00:18:15,720 --> 00:18:19,223
Mr President. Honoured.
I'm on the fast-track programme.

263
00:18:19,307 --> 00:18:22,560
Cybus Industries have bought up
my company so I'm part of the firm now.

264
00:18:22,643 --> 00:18:25,271
Some people say
they've bought my government.

265
00:18:25,354 --> 00:18:28,232
I've never heard anybody say that. Never.

266
00:18:29,567 --> 00:18:31,193
You can trust me on this.

267
00:18:31,277 --> 00:18:35,823
I tried your drink, that Vitex stuff.
It tastes like pop.

268
00:18:36,157 --> 00:18:37,533
Well, it is pop.

269
00:18:37,658 --> 00:18:41,203
You've made money by selling
a health food drink to a sick world.

270
00:18:41,287 --> 00:18:44,915
Not quite the ordinary Joe
you appear to be, are you?

271
00:18:46,292 --> 00:18:50,046
(SIGHING) He does like to keep us waiting.

272
00:18:51,881 --> 00:18:56,719
But tell me, you've had a chance
to observe John Lumic more than most.

273
00:18:57,386 --> 00:18:59,263
What's your opinion?

274
00:19:00,181 --> 00:19:03,392
He's very sharp, I'd say, sharp as ever.

275
00:19:03,517 --> 00:19:06,479
Very clever man. Brilliant, in fact.

276
00:19:06,562 --> 00:19:08,814
Then you don't think he's insane?

277
00:19:08,898 --> 00:19:11,275
It's not the word I would've used, no.

278
00:19:11,776 --> 00:19:12,985
I see.

279
00:19:36,926 --> 00:19:38,552
-Am I all right to go past?
-Yeah.

280
00:19:38,636 --> 00:19:41,931
No bother. Curfew doesn't start till 10:00.

281
00:19:42,098 --> 00:19:44,392
-There's a curfew?
-Course there is.

282
00:19:44,475 --> 00:19:47,978
Where you been living, mate?
Up there with the toffs?

283
00:19:51,273 --> 00:19:52,650
I wish.

284
00:19:55,277 --> 00:19:56,779
See you.

285
00:20:06,622 --> 00:20:08,833
Mickey's mum just couldn't cope.

286
00:20:10,876 --> 00:20:14,630
His dad hung around for a while,
but then he just sort of wandered off.

287
00:20:14,714 --> 00:20:20,219
He was brought up by his gran.
She was such a great woman.

288
00:20:20,302 --> 00:20:23,431
God, she used to slap him!

289
00:20:24,056 --> 00:20:27,643
But then she died.
She tripped and fell down the stairs.

290
00:20:28,436 --> 00:20:31,605
It was about five years ago now.
I was still in school.

291
00:20:32,273 --> 00:20:33,649
I never knew.

292
00:20:33,733 --> 00:20:35,985
-Well, you never asked.
-You never said.

293
00:20:36,068 --> 00:20:39,447
That's Mickey. I suppose...

294
00:20:39,530 --> 00:20:42,408
we just take him for granted.

295
00:20:43,826 --> 00:20:46,996
-Do you think she's still alive? His gran?
-Could be.

296
00:20:47,121 --> 00:20:49,790
Like I said, parallel world,
gingerbread house.

297
00:20:49,874 --> 00:20:52,293
We need to get out of here
as fast as we can.

298
00:20:52,376 --> 00:20:55,379
(BEEPING)

299
00:20:59,884 --> 00:21:02,052
What are they all doing?

300
00:21:02,136 --> 00:21:04,013
They've stopped.

301
00:21:21,405 --> 00:21:23,699
It's the ear pieces.

302
00:21:25,659 --> 00:21:29,330
Like Bluetooth attachments
but everyone's connected together.

303
00:21:29,413 --> 00:21:31,040
(BEEPING)

304
00:21:32,166 --> 00:21:36,045
It's on my phone. It's automatic.
Look, it's downloading.

305
00:21:36,128 --> 00:21:38,631
Is this what they're all getting?

306
00:21:40,883 --> 00:21:45,346
ROSE: News, international news,
sport, weather.

307
00:21:45,805 --> 00:21:50,226
They get it direct.
Downloaded right into their heads.

308
00:21:50,810 --> 00:21:53,521
TV schedules, lottery numbers.

309
00:21:53,687 --> 00:21:56,398
Everyone shares the same information.

310
00:21:57,233 --> 00:22:00,861
Daily download,
published by Cybus Industries.

311
00:22:01,278 --> 00:22:03,739
(ALL LAUGHING)

312
00:22:10,246 --> 00:22:12,998
You lot, you're obsessed.
You'll do anything for the latest upgrade.

313
00:22:13,082 --> 00:22:16,168
Oi, they're not my lot.
Different world, remember?

314
00:22:16,252 --> 00:22:19,338
It's not so far off your world.
This place is only parallel.

315
00:22:19,421 --> 00:22:21,298
Oh, look at that.

316
00:22:21,382 --> 00:22:26,345
Cybus Industries, owners of just about
every company in Britain, including Vitex.

317
00:22:26,428 --> 00:22:29,473
Mr Pete Tyler's very well connected.

318
00:22:36,105 --> 00:22:38,774
Okay, I give up. Let's go and see him.

319
00:22:56,292 --> 00:22:58,335
WOMAN: Who's that there?

320
00:23:01,672 --> 00:23:04,592
Who is it? I know you're there.

321
00:23:04,675 --> 00:23:08,387
Shame on you, tricking an old lady.
I've got nothing worth stealing.

322
00:23:08,470 --> 00:23:12,433
And don't think I'm gonna disappear.
You're not gonna take me!

323
00:23:12,516 --> 00:23:13,642
Hi.

324
00:23:16,854 --> 00:23:18,981
Is that you?

325
00:23:19,064 --> 00:23:21,025
It's me. I came home.

326
00:23:21,150 --> 00:23:22,484
Ricky!

327
00:23:22,651 --> 00:23:24,153
It's Mickey.

328
00:23:24,278 --> 00:23:28,949
I know my own grandson's name.
It's Ricky. Now come here.

329
00:23:32,745 --> 00:23:37,082
Okay, I'm Ricky. Of course I am.
Ricky, that's me.

330
00:23:38,125 --> 00:23:40,127
-You stupid boy!
-Ow!

331
00:23:40,210 --> 00:23:42,254
-Where've you been?
-Stop hitting me!

332
00:23:42,338 --> 00:23:44,381
It's been days and days.

333
00:23:44,465 --> 00:23:48,010
I keep hearing all these stories,
people disappearing off the street.

334
00:23:48,093 --> 00:23:50,763
There's nothing official on the download

335
00:23:50,846 --> 00:23:53,974
but there are all these rumours
and whispers.

336
00:23:54,058 --> 00:23:57,311
I thought they'd gone and disappeared you.

337
00:23:57,394 --> 00:24:00,689
That carpet on the stairs,
I told you to get it fixed. You're gonna...

338
00:24:00,814 --> 00:24:02,274
fall and break your neck.

339
00:24:02,358 --> 00:24:04,276
Well, you get it fixed for me!

340
00:24:04,360 --> 00:24:07,571
I should've done it way back.
I guess I'm just kind of useless.

341
00:24:07,655 --> 00:24:10,157
Now, I never said that.

342
00:24:10,240 --> 00:24:12,159
I am, though.

343
00:24:12,242 --> 00:24:14,411
And I'm sorry, Gran. I'm so sorry.

344
00:24:14,495 --> 00:24:18,123
Don't talk like that.
Do you know what you need?

345
00:24:18,874 --> 00:24:21,710
A nice sit down and a cup of tea.

346
00:24:22,378 --> 00:24:25,756
-You got time?
-For you, I've got all the time in the world.

347
00:24:25,839 --> 00:24:29,051
Oh, you say that but it's all talk.

348
00:24:30,260 --> 00:24:34,014
It's those new friends of yours.
I don't trust them.

349
00:24:34,098 --> 00:24:36,976
-What friends are they?
-Don't pretend you don't know.

350
00:24:37,059 --> 00:24:39,687
You've been seen. Mrs Chan told me.

351
00:24:39,770 --> 00:24:42,564
Driving about,
all helter-skelter, in that van.

352
00:24:42,648 --> 00:24:44,483
What van's that, then?

353
00:24:44,566 --> 00:24:47,027
You know full well.
Don't play games with me.

354
00:24:48,737 --> 00:24:50,614
Get inside.

355
00:24:53,742 --> 00:24:56,286
I've been looking for you everywhere!

356
00:25:00,874 --> 00:25:02,876
Ricky. Ricky!

357
00:25:03,085 --> 00:25:04,962
Ricky, you were the one who told us.

358
00:25:05,045 --> 00:25:07,673
You don't contact your family
'cause it puts them in danger.

359
00:25:07,756 --> 00:25:10,926
Yeah. Ricky said that.
Course I did. Just testing.

360
00:25:11,010 --> 00:25:13,137
I saw them. I taped them.

361
00:25:13,220 --> 00:25:16,724
They went round Blackfriars gathering up
the homeless like the Child Catcher.

362
00:25:16,807 --> 00:25:18,517
They must have took four dozen.

363
00:25:18,600 --> 00:25:23,230
The vans were hired out to a company
called International Electromatics.

364
00:25:23,772 --> 00:25:25,357
But I did a protocol search,

365
00:25:25,441 --> 00:25:28,944
turns out that's a dummy company
established by guess who?

366
00:25:29,611 --> 00:25:30,863
I don't know. Who?

367
00:25:30,946 --> 00:25:33,198
TOGETHER: Cybus Industries!

368
00:25:33,282 --> 00:25:34,950
Well, now we've got evidence!

369
00:25:35,034 --> 00:25:37,661
Bad news is they've arrested Thin Jimmy.

370
00:25:37,745 --> 00:25:40,831
-So that just leaves you.
-Leaves me what?

371
00:25:40,914 --> 00:25:42,583
The number one.

372
00:25:42,666 --> 00:25:44,168
Top of the list.

373
00:25:44,251 --> 00:25:46,295
London's most wanted.

374
00:25:46,378 --> 00:25:48,297
Okay. Cool.

375
00:25:49,381 --> 00:25:50,966
Say that again.

376
00:25:51,425 --> 00:25:54,053
LUMIC: 7he most precious thing
on this earth is the human brain

377
00:25:54,136 --> 00:25:55,804
and yet we allow it to die.

378
00:25:55,888 --> 00:25:59,266
But now Cybus Industries
has perfected a way

379
00:25:59,349 --> 00:26:04,563
of sustaining the brain indefinitely
within a cradle of copyrighted chemicals.

380
00:26:04,980 --> 00:26:08,150
And the latest advances
in synapse research

381
00:26:08,233 --> 00:26:13,363
allows cyberkinetic impulses
to be bonded onto a metal exoskeleton.

382
00:26:13,655 --> 00:26:15,908
This is the ultimate upgrade.

383
00:26:15,991 --> 00:26:19,078
Our greatest step into cyberspace.

384
00:26:19,161 --> 00:26:22,164
I'm sorry, could we stop it there?

385
00:26:22,956 --> 00:26:27,669
I don't need the pitch. I think we all know
what this ultimate upgrade entails.

386
00:26:28,295 --> 00:26:30,172
And I'm here to tell you, John,

387
00:26:30,255 --> 00:26:32,007
the answer is no.

388
00:26:32,841 --> 00:26:35,427
My government
does not give you permission.

389
00:26:36,678 --> 00:26:39,056
And I think no government ever will.

390
00:26:39,223 --> 00:26:42,017
I've prepared a paper
for the Ethical Committee.

391
00:26:42,101 --> 00:26:43,560
Oh, come on!

392
00:26:43,644 --> 00:26:46,688
It's not just unethical, it's obscene.

393
00:26:46,772 --> 00:26:50,776
Mr President,
if I might make a personal plea.

394
00:26:51,026 --> 00:26:52,653
I am dying, sir.

395
00:26:52,736 --> 00:26:54,696
I'm aware of that.

396
00:26:54,780 --> 00:26:56,490
And I'm very sorry.

397
00:26:56,573 --> 00:26:59,451
Without this project,
you have condemned me.

398
00:27:00,202 --> 00:27:03,747
My inventions have advanced
this whole planet.

399
00:27:05,040 --> 00:27:07,042
Would you have all that perish?

400
00:27:07,126 --> 00:27:09,795
You're a fine businessman, John.

401
00:27:09,878 --> 00:27:11,713
But you're not God.

402
00:27:13,757 --> 00:27:17,636
I'm really very sorry
but I think we should end it there.

403
00:27:18,720 --> 00:27:21,473
Mr Tyler, I'll see you tonight.

404
00:27:21,807 --> 00:27:24,560
I think we could all do with a drink.

405
00:27:25,310 --> 00:27:26,603
Mr Lumic.

406
00:27:36,446 --> 00:27:40,159
Still, it's not the only country
in the world. There's always New Germany.

407
00:27:40,242 --> 00:27:42,077
This is the homeland.

408
00:27:42,161 --> 00:27:43,871
My birthplace.

409
00:27:44,496 --> 00:27:46,039
You may leave.

410
00:27:46,123 --> 00:27:47,833
Thank you, sir.

411
00:27:53,213 --> 00:27:54,715
Mr Crane!

412
00:27:55,340 --> 00:27:56,842
Ready and waiting, sir.

413
00:27:56,925 --> 00:27:59,011
Did the override work?

414
00:27:59,094 --> 00:28:02,973
Well, it needs a bit of fine tuning.
We weren't exactly delicate given the rush.

415
00:28:03,098 --> 00:28:05,809
But, yeah, yeah, it's all working.

416
00:28:06,894 --> 00:28:09,146
I've been testing the system, sir.

417
00:28:12,608 --> 00:28:15,611
They've grafted on a treat, these have.

418
00:28:15,694 --> 00:28:17,446
Given a little persuasion.

419
00:28:17,571 --> 00:28:19,823
If you'd care to observe, sir.

420
00:28:22,826 --> 00:28:25,996
And turn to the right.

421
00:28:27,956 --> 00:28:30,626
And back to the left.

422
00:28:31,293 --> 00:28:33,670
Are you having fun, Mr Crane?

423
00:28:33,795 --> 00:28:38,175
No, no, not at all, sir, no.
It's just... Well, it's irresistible.

424
00:28:38,300 --> 00:28:41,470
Then resist and start the upgrade.

425
00:28:41,929 --> 00:28:43,180
Did we get permission?

426
00:28:43,305 --> 00:28:46,475
I am governed by greater laws, old friend.

427
00:28:46,558 --> 00:28:49,937
The right of a man to survive. Now begin!

428
00:28:52,898 --> 00:28:55,359
And turn to the left.

429
00:28:57,110 --> 00:28:58,695
Forward march.

430
00:29:01,990 --> 00:29:03,325
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

431
00:29:03,408 --> 00:29:04,868
(SCREAMING)

432
00:29:04,993 --> 00:29:09,873
Whoa! Let's cover up that noise.
Give us track number 19.

433
00:29:10,749 --> 00:29:14,419
(THE LION SLEEPS TONIGHT
BY TIGHT FIT PLAYING)

434
00:29:19,675 --> 00:29:22,636
(SCREAMING)

435
00:29:43,448 --> 00:29:45,742
(MEN WAILING)

436
00:29:49,746 --> 00:29:52,124
There's a light on.
There's someone inside the base.

437
00:29:52,207 --> 00:29:54,209
Mrs Moore, we've got visitors.

438
00:29:59,840 --> 00:30:03,427
One, two, three, go!

439
00:30:05,387 --> 00:30:07,347
What the hell are you doing?

440
00:30:08,515 --> 00:30:10,225
What are you doing there?

441
00:30:10,976 --> 00:30:12,561
What am I doing here?

442
00:30:15,105 --> 00:30:16,732
What am I doing there?

443
00:30:24,906 --> 00:30:27,242
They've got visitors.

444
00:30:27,326 --> 00:30:29,536
February the 1st. Mum's birthday.

445
00:30:31,079 --> 00:30:34,166
Even in a parallel universe,
she still loves a party.

446
00:30:34,249 --> 00:30:37,461
Well, given Pete Tyler's guest list,
I wouldn't mind a look.

447
00:30:37,586 --> 00:30:40,005
And there is one guaranteed way
of getting inside...

448
00:30:40,088 --> 00:30:41,673
Psychic paper.

449
00:30:41,757 --> 00:30:43,675
Who do you want to be?

450
00:30:43,842 --> 00:30:45,427
(BOTTLE POPPING)

451
00:30:56,438 --> 00:30:59,358
-We could've been anyone.
-It got us in, didn't it?

452
00:30:59,441 --> 00:31:02,527
You're in charge of the psychic paper.
We could've been guests.

453
00:31:02,652 --> 00:31:05,447
Celebrities. Sir Doctor, Dame Rose.

454
00:31:05,572 --> 00:31:08,784
And we end up serving.
I did enough of this back home.

455
00:31:09,868 --> 00:31:12,788
If you want to know what's going on,
work in the kitchen.

456
00:31:17,334 --> 00:31:20,962
-According to Lucy, that man over there...
-Who's Lucy?

457
00:31:21,671 --> 00:31:24,257
She's carrying the salmon pinwheels.

458
00:31:24,341 --> 00:31:27,302
-Oh, that's Lucy, is it?
-Yeah.

459
00:31:27,427 --> 00:31:30,639
Lucy says
that is the President of Great Britain.

460
00:31:30,764 --> 00:31:32,474
What, there's a president,
not a prime minister?

461
00:31:32,557 --> 00:31:34,226
Seems so.

462
00:31:34,309 --> 00:31:37,479
Or maybe Lucy's just a bit thick.

463
00:31:43,652 --> 00:31:46,405
PETE: Excuse me, thank you very much.

464
00:31:46,488 --> 00:31:49,533
Thank you,
if I could have your attention please.

465
00:31:49,658 --> 00:31:52,786
MAN 1: Come on, Pete.
PETE: Thank you very much.

466
00:31:55,497 --> 00:31:59,793
I'd just like to say thank you to you all
for coming

467
00:31:59,918 --> 00:32:01,837
on this very special occasion.

468
00:32:01,920 --> 00:32:03,338
My wife's...

469
00:32:03,422 --> 00:32:04,673
39th.

470
00:32:04,798 --> 00:32:06,466
(ALL LAUGHING)

471
00:32:06,967 --> 00:32:09,261
Trust me on this.

472
00:32:09,344 --> 00:32:12,222
And so without any further ado, here she is,

473
00:32:12,347 --> 00:32:15,684
the birthday girl, my lovely wife,

474
00:32:16,476 --> 00:32:17,644
Jackie Tyler.

475
00:32:26,403 --> 00:32:28,530
Now, I'm not giving a speech,

476
00:32:28,655 --> 00:32:31,741
that's what my parties are famous for,
no work, no politics.

477
00:32:31,867 --> 00:32:35,162
Just a few good mates
and plenty of black market whisky.

478
00:32:37,164 --> 00:32:39,499
Pardon me, Mr President.

479
00:32:39,583 --> 00:32:42,878
So, yeah, get on with it. Enjoy! Enjoy.

480
00:32:42,961 --> 00:32:45,005
(ALL CHEERING)

481
00:32:48,842 --> 00:32:51,470
You can't stay. Even if there was
some way of telling them.

482
00:32:51,553 --> 00:32:53,263
Course I can't.

483
00:32:53,346 --> 00:32:56,975
I've still got Mum at home, my real mum.
I couldn't just leave her, could I?

484
00:32:57,058 --> 00:32:58,643
It's just...

485
00:33:00,353 --> 00:33:01,938
They've got each other.

486
00:33:03,398 --> 00:33:04,691
Mum's got no one.

487
00:33:04,774 --> 00:33:07,277
She's got you. Those two haven't.

488
00:33:09,029 --> 00:33:11,490
All these different worlds,
not one of them gets it right.

489
00:33:11,573 --> 00:33:13,241
JACKIE: Rose!

490
00:33:13,325 --> 00:33:17,078
Here's my little girl!
Come to mummy, come to mummy, yes.

491
00:33:18,788 --> 00:33:20,832
Good girl, aren't you!

492
00:33:26,880 --> 00:33:28,340
Sorry.

493
00:33:32,093 --> 00:33:35,263
MECHANICAL VOICE:
Platoon 02 now boarding.

494
00:33:35,388 --> 00:33:38,600
Platoon 02 now boarding.

495
00:33:41,311 --> 00:33:43,188
Stop staring.

496
00:33:43,271 --> 00:33:46,942
-But what are they, sir?
-I'm told they're the future.

497
00:33:47,025 --> 00:33:49,152
Ain't technology wonderful?

498
00:33:49,277 --> 00:33:51,905
Go on, get to the cab, start her up.

499
00:33:51,988 --> 00:33:53,406
Sir.

500
00:33:53,698 --> 00:33:56,117
(RINGING)

501
00:33:56,201 --> 00:33:58,912
LUMIC: Mr Crane, are we mobile?

502
00:33:58,995 --> 00:34:01,873
Just about to hit the road, sir.
And yourself?

503
00:34:02,082 --> 00:34:05,669
I'm arriving, Mr Crane. Prepare the factory.

504
00:34:05,794 --> 00:34:07,587
(ZEPPELIN WHIRRING)

505
00:34:07,671 --> 00:34:12,133
Now send them forth, old friend.
Let the good work begin.

506
00:34:15,428 --> 00:34:17,681
(BEEPING)

507
00:34:27,899 --> 00:34:30,026
He's clean. No bugs.

508
00:34:30,151 --> 00:34:31,903
But this is off the scale.

509
00:34:33,488 --> 00:34:35,574
He's flesh and blood. How did that happen?

510
00:34:35,657 --> 00:34:38,743
Well, it could be that Cybus Industries

511
00:34:38,827 --> 00:34:41,871
have perfected the science
of human cloning.

512
00:34:41,997 --> 00:34:44,040
Or, your father had a bike.

513
00:34:48,503 --> 00:34:50,922
And your name's Mickey, not Ricky?

514
00:34:51,006 --> 00:34:52,382
Mickey.

515
00:34:52,465 --> 00:34:56,094
Dad was Jackson Smith, used to work
at the key cutter's on Clifton Parade.

516
00:34:56,177 --> 00:34:58,513
Went to Spain, never came back.

517
00:35:00,265 --> 00:35:01,933
But that's my dad.

518
00:35:03,268 --> 00:35:06,313
So...we're brothers?

519
00:35:06,521 --> 00:35:08,607
Be fair, what else could it be?

520
00:35:09,274 --> 00:35:10,609
I don't know.

521
00:35:12,193 --> 00:35:16,072
But he doesn't just look like me.
He is exactly the same.

522
00:35:16,573 --> 00:35:18,491
There's something else going on here, Jake.

523
00:35:18,617 --> 00:35:19,826
So who are you lot?

524
00:35:19,909 --> 00:35:23,330
We? We are the Preachers.

525
00:35:23,913 --> 00:35:25,415
As in "gospel truth”.

526
00:35:26,583 --> 00:35:29,294
Do you see? No Ear Pods.

527
00:35:29,377 --> 00:35:31,963
While the rest of the world
downloads from Cybus Industries,

528
00:35:32,047 --> 00:35:35,133
we have got freedom.

529
00:35:36,843 --> 00:35:39,387
You're talking to London's most wanted.

530
00:35:40,597 --> 00:35:44,851
But target number one is Lumic
and we are going to bring him down.

531
00:35:46,061 --> 00:35:47,937
From your kitchen?

532
00:35:50,899 --> 00:35:52,817
Have you got a problem with that?

533
00:35:52,901 --> 00:35:54,736
No. It's a good kitchen.

534
00:35:56,154 --> 00:35:57,280
(BEEPING)

535
00:35:57,405 --> 00:36:00,158
-It's an upload from Gemini.
-Who's Gemini?

536
00:36:00,241 --> 00:36:03,870
The vans are back.
They are moving out of Battersea.

537
00:36:03,953 --> 00:36:06,081
Looks like Gemini was right,

538
00:36:06,206 --> 00:36:07,957
Lumic's finally making a move.

539
00:36:08,083 --> 00:36:10,377
And we are right behind him.
Pack up, we're leaving.

540
00:36:10,460 --> 00:36:12,379
(HORN BLARING)

541
00:37:21,406 --> 00:37:23,241
I remember her 21st.

542
00:37:23,324 --> 00:37:25,410
Pint of cider in the George.

543
00:37:26,578 --> 00:37:28,204
Sorry, sir, champagne?

544
00:37:29,622 --> 00:37:31,875
Might as well, I'm paying for it.

545
00:37:34,169 --> 00:37:36,087
Big night for you.

546
00:37:36,171 --> 00:37:37,505
For her.

547
00:37:38,506 --> 00:37:40,508
Still, she's happy.

548
00:37:40,633 --> 00:37:43,261
Yeah, she should be. It's a great party.

549
00:37:43,344 --> 00:37:44,888
Do you think?

550
00:37:46,055 --> 00:37:48,975
-You can trust me!
-"You can trust me on this."

551
00:37:49,058 --> 00:37:51,019
That's it, sorry. Yeah.

552
00:37:52,562 --> 00:37:55,940
So, how long have you two been married?

553
00:37:56,357 --> 00:37:57,525
20 years.

554
00:37:57,942 --> 00:37:59,694
No kids, or...

555
00:38:00,779 --> 00:38:02,697
We kept putting it off.

556
00:38:04,115 --> 00:38:06,618
She said she didn't want to spoil her figure.

557
00:38:08,620 --> 00:38:10,413
It's not too late. She's only 40.

558
00:38:10,538 --> 00:38:11,831
39.

559
00:38:11,915 --> 00:38:14,459
All right, 39.

560
00:38:16,294 --> 00:38:17,879
It's still too late.

561
00:38:18,546 --> 00:38:20,173
I moved out last month.

562
00:38:21,090 --> 00:38:24,135
We're gonna keep it quiet, you know.
It's bad for business.

563
00:38:28,056 --> 00:38:31,434
Why am I telling you all this?
We haven't met before, have we?

564
00:38:32,519 --> 00:38:34,938
-I don't know, you just seem sort of...
-What?

565
00:38:36,898 --> 00:38:38,733
I don't know. Just sort of...

566
00:38:40,902 --> 00:38:42,111
right.

567
00:38:45,240 --> 00:38:48,451
Stevie, how's things?
How's it going at Torchwood?

568
00:38:53,790 --> 00:38:57,210
I don't know what they're doing,
but this seems to be the target.

569
00:38:57,293 --> 00:39:01,381
Big house, fair bit of money.
Now we've got to find a way to get in there.

570
00:39:01,464 --> 00:39:03,883
I've identified the address,

571
00:39:03,967 --> 00:39:07,929
it belongs to Peter Tyler,
the Vitex millionaire.

572
00:39:08,096 --> 00:39:09,347
Pete Tyler?

573
00:39:09,430 --> 00:39:13,434
He's listed as one of Lumic's henchmen,
a traitor to the state.

574
00:39:14,227 --> 00:39:17,146
But... We've got to get in there!

575
00:39:17,230 --> 00:39:19,440
Now shut it, duplicate.
That's what I just said.

576
00:39:21,609 --> 00:39:22,902
What are they doing?

577
00:39:23,027 --> 00:39:24,487
(HEAVY FOOTSTEPS)

578
00:39:28,449 --> 00:39:30,118
What the hell are they?

579
00:39:36,624 --> 00:39:39,961
LUMIC: 7he most precious thing
on this earth is the human brain...

580
00:39:50,138 --> 00:39:52,765
Mrs Tyler, is there anything I can get you?

581
00:39:54,058 --> 00:39:56,311
The last 20 years back.

582
00:39:59,314 --> 00:40:01,941
I could manage a glass of champagne.

583
00:40:02,025 --> 00:40:04,819
-Or a nice cup of tea?
-Oh, that'd do me.

584
00:40:07,322 --> 00:40:08,907
My mum loves that.

585
00:40:08,990 --> 00:40:10,867
End of a long night,
she never goes straight to bed.

586
00:40:10,992 --> 00:40:13,119
She always stays up
just to have that last cup of tea.

587
00:40:13,202 --> 00:40:14,996
Oh, I'm the same.

588
00:40:15,538 --> 00:40:17,123
-Two sugars.
-And me.

589
00:40:17,206 --> 00:40:19,626
And Pete always says, you know...

590
00:40:22,045 --> 00:40:23,671
Never mind him.

591
00:40:25,131 --> 00:40:28,426
I was talking to him earlier.
He's a nice man.

592
00:40:29,344 --> 00:40:32,680
You know, a bit of a Jack the lad,
I suppose, even if he has got money.

593
00:40:32,805 --> 00:40:35,642
But he's a good bloke.

594
00:40:37,685 --> 00:40:38,978
Better than most.

595
00:40:42,023 --> 00:40:43,524
He's worth a second chance.

596
00:40:44,567 --> 00:40:46,861
Are you commenting on my marriage?

597
00:40:47,612 --> 00:40:48,780
No, I was just...

598
00:40:48,863 --> 00:40:51,532
Who the hell do you think you are?
You're staff.

599
00:40:51,699 --> 00:40:55,119
You're nothing but staff. You're just
the serving girl for God's sake!

600
00:40:55,203 --> 00:40:57,538
And you are certainly not getting paid.

601
00:40:57,622 --> 00:40:59,707
Don't you dare talk to me.

602
00:41:12,053 --> 00:41:14,472
(LOUD FOOTSTEPS)

603
00:41:22,146 --> 00:41:27,360
LUMIC: 7his is the ultimate upgrade.
Our greatest step into cyberspace.

604
00:41:27,485 --> 00:41:28,736
Cybus.

605
00:41:57,056 --> 00:41:59,058
It's happening again.

606
00:41:59,726 --> 00:42:01,269
What do you mean?

607
00:42:01,394 --> 00:42:03,438
I've seen them before.

608
00:42:05,565 --> 00:42:06,858
What are they?

609
00:42:06,941 --> 00:42:08,151
Cybermen.

610
00:42:08,276 --> 00:42:10,695
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

611
00:42:30,089 --> 00:42:31,466
Mr Lumic.

612
00:42:31,549 --> 00:42:35,970
Mr President. I suppose a remark
about crashing the party

613
00:42:36,054 --> 00:42:38,806
would be appropriate at this point, sir.

614
00:42:38,931 --> 00:42:40,266
I forbade this.

615
00:42:40,349 --> 00:42:42,185
These are my children, sir.

616
00:42:42,310 --> 00:42:44,312
Would you deny my family?

617
00:42:45,063 --> 00:42:48,316
-What are they? Robots?
-Worse than that.

618
00:42:48,399 --> 00:42:50,985
-Who were these people?
-It doesn't matter.

619
00:42:51,110 --> 00:42:52,987
They're people?

620
00:42:53,071 --> 00:42:56,741
They were.
Till they had all their humanity taken away.

621
00:42:57,492 --> 00:43:00,578
That's a living brain
jammed inside a cybernetic body.

622
00:43:00,661 --> 00:43:04,373
With a heart of steel,
all emotions removed.

623
00:43:04,832 --> 00:43:06,375
Why no emotions?

624
00:43:07,460 --> 00:43:08,795
Because it hurts.

625
00:43:08,878 --> 00:43:12,256
I demand to know, Lumic, these people,
who were they?

626
00:43:12,340 --> 00:43:14,759
They were homeless
and wretched and useless,

627
00:43:14,842 --> 00:43:17,303
until I saved them, and elevated them,

628
00:43:17,386 --> 00:43:19,347
and gave them life eternal.

629
00:43:20,181 --> 00:43:23,518
And now I leave you
in their capable hands. Good night, sir.

630
00:43:23,601 --> 00:43:25,686
Good night, Mr President.

631
00:43:27,814 --> 00:43:29,899
CYBERMAN: We have been upgraded.

632
00:43:30,274 --> 00:43:31,818
Into what?

633
00:43:31,901 --> 00:43:34,195
The next level of mankind.

634
00:43:34,278 --> 00:43:36,072
We are Human Point Two.

635
00:43:36,239 --> 00:43:39,534
Every citizen will receive a free upgrade.

636
00:43:39,617 --> 00:43:41,661
You will become like us.

637
00:43:41,744 --> 00:43:44,122
I'm sorry.

638
00:43:44,664 --> 00:43:47,708
I'm so sorry for what's been done to you.

639
00:43:48,167 --> 00:43:49,585
But listen to me.

640
00:43:50,670 --> 00:43:54,132
This experiment ends tonight.

641
00:43:54,549 --> 00:43:56,884
Upgrading is compulsory.

642
00:43:57,718 --> 00:44:00,054
-And if I refuse?
-Don't.

643
00:44:00,138 --> 00:44:01,681
What if I refuse?

644
00:44:01,764 --> 00:44:03,099
I'm telling you, don't!

645
00:44:03,224 --> 00:44:05,852
What happens if I refuse?

646
00:44:06,394 --> 00:44:09,230
Then you are not compatible.

647
00:44:10,481 --> 00:44:12,108
What happens then?

648
00:44:13,192 --> 00:44:15,027
You will be deleted.

649
00:44:20,074 --> 00:44:22,410
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

650
00:44:22,785 --> 00:44:24,287
Jackie?

651
00:44:26,539 --> 00:44:28,583
PETE: Jackie?

652
00:44:37,592 --> 00:44:39,510
DOCTOR: There's nothing we can do.

653
00:44:39,719 --> 00:44:41,596
But my mum's in there.

654
00:44:41,679 --> 00:44:43,723
She's not your mother, come on!

655
00:44:52,398 --> 00:44:54,317
Pete! Pete!

656
00:45:23,429 --> 00:45:26,307
-Pete, is there a way out?
-The side gates.

657
00:45:26,390 --> 00:45:28,100
Who are you? How do you know so much?

658
00:45:28,184 --> 00:45:30,436
DOCTOR: You wouldn't believe it
in a million years.

659
00:45:36,692 --> 00:45:38,402
Who's that?

660
00:45:38,527 --> 00:45:40,029
RICKY: Get behind me!

661
00:45:52,166 --> 00:45:54,085
Oh, my God, look at you!

662
00:45:54,168 --> 00:45:56,504
I thought I'd never see you again.

663
00:45:58,005 --> 00:46:00,841
Yeah, no offence, sweetheart,
but who the hell are you?

664
00:46:00,925 --> 00:46:02,385
Rose!

665
00:46:03,302 --> 00:46:06,055
That's not me. That's, like, the other one.

666
00:46:06,681 --> 00:46:09,267
Oh, as if things weren't bad enough,
there's two Mickeys!

667
00:46:09,350 --> 00:46:11,852
-It's Ricky.
-But there's more of them.

668
00:46:11,978 --> 00:46:13,396
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

669
00:46:15,398 --> 00:46:17,108
We're surrounded.

670
00:46:17,191 --> 00:46:19,652
Put the guns down.
Bullets won't stop them.

671
00:46:20,319 --> 00:46:22,947
You! Stop shooting! Now!

672
00:46:24,031 --> 00:46:25,533
We surrender.

673
00:46:26,200 --> 00:46:27,576
Hands up.

674
00:46:30,121 --> 00:46:33,165
There's no need to damage us.
We're good stock.

675
00:46:34,083 --> 00:46:38,087
We volunteer for the upgrade programme.
Take us to be processed.

676
00:46:38,212 --> 00:46:40,131
You are rogue elements.

677
00:46:40,214 --> 00:46:41,465
But we surrender.

678
00:46:41,549 --> 00:46:43,551
You are incompatible.

679
00:46:43,634 --> 00:46:45,136
But this is a surrender!

680
00:46:45,219 --> 00:46:47,388
You will be deleted.

681
00:46:47,513 --> 00:46:49,724
But we're surrendering!
Listen to me! We surrender!

682
00:46:49,849 --> 00:46:51,475
You are inferior.

683
00:46:51,559 --> 00:46:54,228
Man will be reborn as Cyberman

684
00:46:54,312 --> 00:46:58,107
but you will perish
under maximum deletion.

685
00:47:00,484 --> 00:47:04,572
Delete. Delete. Delete. Delete.

